ewcommand{\ord}{\mathrm{ord}}$ I want to calculate $\int_{\partial B_2(0)}  rac{\mathrm{d}z}{(z-3)(z^{13}-1)}  $ using residue theorem. I want to keep it very simple.  The exercise is taken from Freitag, Complex Analysis. The solution is given by $-2\pi i (3^{13}-1)$. He solved it with a theorem we never had in lecture. My Idea: $I:=\int_{\partial B_2(0)}  rac{\mathrm{d}z}{(z-3)(z^{13}-1)}$  egin{align*}  I&= 2 \pi i \sum_{j=1}^{k} es(f(z),z_j) \underbrace{\ind(2 \mathrm{e}^{2\pi i t}, z_j )}_{=1} \  &= 2 \pi i  igg[ es( f,3) + es(f,1) + es(f,-(-1)^{1/13}) + es(f, (-1)^{2/13}) \  &+ \dots + es(f, (-1)^{12/13})   igg]  \  &= 2 \pi i  igg[  rac{1}{3^{13} -1} -  rac{1}{26} +  es(f,-(-1)^{1/13}) + es(f, (-1)^{2/13}) + \dots + es(f, (-1)^{12/13})  igg] \end{align*} I used $es(f/g,a) = f(a)/g'(a)$ with $f(z)=1$, $g(z)=(z-3)(z^{13}-1)$ and  $g'(z) = -3(z^{13}-1) + (z-3)13z^{2}$.  Now I have to calculate all these residues, but is there some faster way ?

